The Responsible Social Media Checklist

5 Do's: Build Your Brand

Do Curate Your Privacy Settings: Regularly audit who can see your posts and who can tag you in photos. It’s better to have a "professional" public face and a "personal" private one.

Do Use LinkedIn for Networking: Connect with your professors, seniors at VIT Bhopal, and industry professionals. Share your AIML projects and club achievements there.

Do Fact-Check Before Sharing: In an era of AI-generated misinformation, verify news or academic resources before hitting 'Repost' to maintain your credibility.

Do Highlight Your Skills: Post about your certifications, hackathon participations, or even a cool Minecraft mod you built. It shows you are passionate and active in your field.

Do Engage Respectfully: If you comment on a post or join a discussion, keep the tone constructive. A positive digital footprint is a huge asset during internship season.

5 Don'ts: Protect Your Future

Don't Post Sensitive Info: Never share photos of your student ID, your hostel room number, or your real-time location. This is critical for your physical and digital safety.

Don't "Cyber-Vent": Avoid posting negative rants about your college, faculty, or classmates. Employers often search for a candidate's name to see how they handle frustration.

Don't Ignore the "Permanent" Rule: Never post anything—even in a "disappearing" story—that you wouldn't want a future recruiter to see. Screenshots last forever.

Don't Post During Academic Hours: Avoid sharing content during your lectures or labs. It can give the impression that you aren't focused on your primary responsibilities.

Don't Engage with Trolls: Avoid getting into heated, disrespectful arguments in comment sections. It’s a waste of energy and rarely looks good to an outside observer.
